Section 2 — Architecture & Integration Decisions

1. Auth: magic link only, no password, no Clerk
Buyers are occasional purchasers — a few times a year. Password auth introduces a forgot-password flow, password hashing complexity, and a breach surface for a user segment that barely needs persistent auth. Magic link matches how buyers already use the platform — every order email already contains action links. The MagicLink model, sendEmail infrastructure, and session cookie pattern are all already in the codebase.

Why not Clerk for buyers?
Clerk is used for roaster and org portals — adding a third Clerk app for buyers adds cost, a third key set, and a third webhook to maintain.
Buyers use apps/web, not a portal. A lightweight custom session (HS256 JWT cookie via jose or iron-session) is the right tool.
The magic link pattern already exists in the codebase (MagicLink model + sendEmail). Buyer auth reuses it identically.
SESSION_SECRET is a single new env var. No Clerk dashboard, no Clerk webhook, no Clerk middleware.

2. Checkout integration philosophy
Account creation must never block a purchase. The checkout flow is identical for guest and signed-in buyers — accounts are a benefit layer on top of checkout, not a gate into it. Every account touchpoint in checkout is optional, low visual weight, and provides immediate value when used (pre-filled address, saved card). The post-purchase prompt is the highest-converting moment for account creation because the buyer has just completed a positive action.

